      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Sun and Smoke'' (editorial, July 9):</p>
        <p>The silver lining to the forest-fire clouds last weekend should be a heightened awareness that environmental issues mock arbitrary lines between countries.</p>
        <p>Canada's smoke did not stop at the border for customs, just as shifting weather patterns will bring about an international tangle of droughts, floods and infestations.</p>
        <p>Inhaling Canadian trees for a few days is minor compared with what poor and low-lying countries face from global warming, which the United States accelerates more than any other country.</p>
        <p>Though it won't ever be easy to achieve, politically or logistically, issues of air and water pollution demand international vision, cooperation and action. Maybe we'll continue to look up, and forward, even though the smoke has disappeared.</p>
        <p>DAN CARSEN  Brookline, Mass., July 9, 2002</p>
      </block>
